{"title_page": "International students in Australia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\nAustralia ranked third in top study abroad destinations with a total market value of over 5 million [[Australian dollar|AUD]] (3.47 million [[United States dollar|USD]]) generated by international students in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mastersportal.com/articles/2608/top-9-countries-with-the-highest-investments-in-university-education.html|title=Top 9 Countries With the Highest Investments in University Education - MastersPortal.com|website=www.mastersportal.com|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> With the wishing to gain a high-quality education, have immigration or experience a different life, in 2018, 869,709 international students were enrolled in education program in [[Australia]]<ref name=\":3\" />, which was about 8.8% higher than the amount in 2017 (799,371)<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.studiesinaustralia.com/studying-in-australia/why-study-in-australia/international-students-in-australia|title=International students in Australia|website=Studies in Australia|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>. Each year, many new international students will enrol in Australian courses and add to the already significant international student body around the country.\n\nAustralia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin<ref>https://www.macrobusiness.com.au/2019/11/australian-universities-double-down-on-international-students/</ref>. Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.   International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influcence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-07-27/temporary-graduate-visa-485-boom/10035390</ref>\n\nAccording to the data released by the Departure of Education and Training of the Australian Government, [[China]] is the most significant source of international students to Australia. [[India]] had the second largest proportion of the enrolments, followed by [[Brazil]], [[Nepal]] and [[Malaysia]].<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nAll international students are required to obtain a valid [[student visa]] before they arrive in Australia.<ref name=\":17\" /> When students apply for their student visa through the [[Department of Home Affairs (Australia)|Department of Home Affairs]] of the [[Government of Australia|Australian Government]], they need to submit the electronic Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE) and a compulsory English language proficiency test score to lodge their visa application. Also, each student visa applicant must prove that they have enough financial ability to pay for their tuition fees, books and daily living expenses while they study in Australia.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nAfter the Australian government published the new immigration policy, international students are encouraged to study, work and stay in regional areas in Australia, such as [[Adelaide]], [[Tasmania]] and the [[Northern Territory]]<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/getting-a-visa/visa-listing/skilled-regional-provisional-489/regional-postcodes|title=Postcodes of regional Australia and low population growth metropolitan areas|website=immi.homeaffairs.gov.au|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> . In order to protect the local workforces, the Australian government intends to reduce the number of accepted migrants, and in the long-term, the government aims to set the cap of skilled immigration to about 160,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Definitions ==\nIn Australia, a student is considered as an international student if he/she is not an [[Australian citizen]], [[Australian permanent resident]], [[New Zealander|New Zealand citizen]], or a holder of an Australian permanent resident [[humanitarian visa]].<ref>{{Cite |url=https://www.studyinaustralia.gov.au/Dictionary.aspx?FirstLetter=o |title=Dictionary |website=www.studyinaustralia.gov.au |publisher=Australian Government |date=n.d. |access-date=2019-05-12 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Classification ==\n\n=== By destinations ===\n==== Popular destinations ====\nThe top 3 states in Australia for foreign enrolment in 2018 are listed below.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://internationaleducation.gov.au/research/Research-Snapshots/Documents/Location%20of%20International%20Students%20in%202018.pdf|title=International students studying in regional areas|date=February 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Top 3 states in Australia for foreign enrolment in 2018<ref name=\":2\" />\n!Rank\n!Destination States\n!Number of Students\n!Per cent of Total\n|-\n|1\n|[[New South Wales|NSW]] / [[New South Wales]]\n|333,913\n|38.39%\n|-\n|2\n|[[Victoria (Australia)|VIC]] / [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n|278,975\n|32.08%\n|-\n|3\n|[[Queensland|QLD]] / [[Queensland]]\n|134,312\n|15.44%\n|}\n==== Distribution of International Students in major cities and regional areas ====\n[[File:Distribution of international students in Australia (pie).png|thumb|365x365px|Distribution of International Students in Australia in 2018|alt=]]\nIn 2018, 3% of international students enrolled in Australia stayed in regional locations of Australia, while 97% of international students chose to settle down in major cities<ref name=\":2\" />. All enrolments in Tasmania and the Northern Territory are considered as enrolled in regional areas.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\nNew South Wales had the largest number of international students, up to 333,913. Queensland had the largest regional area proportion (5%), followed by New South Wales (1%) and Victoria (1%)<ref name=\":2\" />.\n[[File:Distribution of international students in Australia (bar chart).png|thumb|364x364px|Distribution of International Students in Australia in 2018|alt=]]\nChina was the main source country for enrolments, which contributed 24% of regional area enrolments. Nepal (7%)<ref name=\":2\" /> had the second large proportion of the regional area enrolments, followed by Malaysia, South Korea and the USA, all of which are contributed three per cent<ref name=\":2\" /> to total regional enrolments. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Distribution of international student enrolments in Australian capital and regional areas in 2018<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://internationaleducation.gov.au/research/DataVisualisations/Pages/Student-number.aspx|title=Student numbers|website=internationaleducation.gov.au|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\" |State / Territory\n! colspan=\"2\" |Share\n! colspan=\"2\" |Enrolments\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Total\n|-\n|Major cities\n|Regional area\n|Major cities\n|Regional area\n|-\n|[[New South Wales|NSW]]\n|99%\n|1%\n|330,224\n|3,689\n|333,913\n|-\n|[[Victoria (Australia)|VIC]]\n|99%\n|1%\n|276,733\n|2,242\n|278,975\n|-\n|[[Queensland|QLD]]\n|95%\n|5%\n|127,260\n|7,052\n|134,312\n|-\n|[[Western Australia|WA]]\n|100%\n|0%\n|51,597\n|233\n|51,830\n|-\n|[[South Australia|SA]]\n|100%\n|0%\n|37,870\n|95\n|37,965\n|-\n|[[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]]\n|100%\n|0%\n|19,286\n| -\n|19,286\n|-\n|[[Tasmania|TAS]]\n| -\n|100%\n| -\n|10,796\n|10,796\n|-\n|[[Northern Territory|NT]]\n| -\n|100%\n| -\n|2,632\n|2,632\n|-\n|[[Australia]] (Total)\n|97%\n|3%\n|842,970\n|26,739\n|869,709\n|}\n\nTop 10 regional centres for international student enrolments in 2018 are listed below.<ref name=\":2\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Regional centres for international student enrolments in 2018<ref name=\":2\" />\n!State / Territory\n!Regional centres\n!2017\n!2018\n!Share\n!Growth in 2017\n|-\n|[[Tasmania|TAS]]\n|[[Hobart]]\n|6,862\n|9,391\n|35%\n|37%\n|-\n|[[Northern Australia|NT]]\n|[[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]]\n|2,462\n|2,625\n|1